  <title>Command Line Interfaces, Again</title>
  <author>
    <name>Toby Inkster</name>
    <email>mail@tobyinkster.co.uk</email>
    <uri>http://tobyinkster.co.uk/</uri>
  </author>
  <content type="text/html" mode="xml">
    <div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p>I posted a couple of years ago that <a href="http://tobyinkster.co.uk/blog/2005/06/08/command-line-interfaces/">the command line is the interface of the future</a>. Today I stumbled on a couple of articles that seem to agree with me:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.humanized.com/weblog/2007/02/24/your_grandmothers_command_line_the_command_line_co/">Command Line for the Common Man: Command Line Comeback</a></li>
<li><a href="http://icr.vox.com/library/post/the-power-of-command-lines.html">The Power of Command Lines</a></li>
</ul>

<p><a href="http://quicksilver.blacktree.com/">Quicksilver</a> blows away both Apple's <a href="http://www.asktog.com/columns/044top10docksucks.html">Dock</a> and Microsoft Windows' <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Windows_Taskbar">Taskbar</a> in terms of speed and usability. And what is it? A command-line interface with a bit of eye-candy.</p>

<p>Command-line really is the way to go.</p></div>
